@Pexo:
> Make it work on Tor Browser in the default config.

It's just going to break in the next version anyway, why bother?

@Filip Š:
> create browser extension which runs ZeruNet Wasm and provides access to ZeroNet without installing it
The biggest problem is that it would not have file storage, so the plugin would always be leech-only.

@styromaniac@zeroid.bit: >there's no reason it wouldn't
You underestimate my ability to introduce bugs :-)
@nekololi: wait until I add the ability to attach images to products ;-p

@Mg0: Zipped galleries **do not** require downloading the entire file before viewing, only the chunks containing the viewed images have to be downloaded. Although the file explorer and ZeroNet files tab may say a zip takes 100mb, it only takes as much disk space as the chunks you've accessed/downloaded.

You may need to upgrade to the latest ZeroNet version if you're having trouble, Anoa and me submitted a bugfix for the Zip behavior last week.

Does this address your concerns?

@ulrichard: From a user's perspective Rust macros are great. I've had a lot of experience with serde and rocket and the amount of work saved by derive macros in particular is priceless.

Diving into writing my own they're on a whole new level. That may just be because I've gotten too comfortable with the kind of Rust I understand. There's a bunch of new syntax to learn, and a couple of libraries like syn and quote and then the hardest part is that I don't know what good macro code should look like.

Here's what happens when your language does not have macros: https://gradha.github.io/articles/2015/01/the-day-go-reinvented-macros.html
